/******************************************** JAVA ******************************************/

Better Solution - we are using some edge cases and sorting the given array to use in a two-pointer solution.
                  This is the best solution I can come up with because other solutions are very complicated and hard to implement 
                   this one is easy to understand.


class Solution {
    public List<List<Integer>> threeSum(int[] nums) {
        // Edge case: if array is null or has fewer than 3 elements,
        // no triplet can sum to zero
        if (nums == null || nums.length < 3) return new ArrayList<>();
        // Sort the array to enable two-pointer technique
        Arrays.sort(nums);
        // Set to store unique triplets (avoids duplicates automatically)
        Set<List<Integer>> set = new HashSet<>();
        // Fix the first element of the triplet one by one
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length - 2; i++) {
            // Initialize two pointers
            int left = i + 1;
            int right = nums.length - 1;
            // Move pointers inward to find pairs that sum with nums[i] to zero
            while (left < right) {
                // Calculate the sum of the triplet
                int sum = nums[i] + nums[left] + nums[right];
                // If sum is zero, we found a valid triplet
                if (sum == 0) {
                    // Add the triplet to the set
                    set.add(Arrays.asList(nums[i], nums[left], nums[right]));
                    // Move both pointers to look for other combinations
                    left++;
                    right--;
                }
                // If sum is less than zero, increase sum by moving left pointer
                else if (sum < 0)
                    left++;
                // If sum is greater than zero, decrease sum by moving right pointer
                else
                    right--;
            }
        }
        // Convert the set to a list and return the result
        return new ArrayList<>(set);
    }
}

Time Complexity :- O(n^2).
Space Complexity :- O(1)
